data.description:
```javascript
let even = n => n === 0 ? true : odd(n-1);
let odd = n => n === 0 ? false : even(n-1);

let sumToN = (n, acc = 0) => n === 0 ? acc : sumToN(n-1, acc+n);
```

Consider the pair of mutually [tail-recursive](http://2ality.com/2015/06/tail-call-optimization.html#tail-recursive-functions) functions (```even``` and ```odd```) above. It naively determines if a non-negative integer is even or odd.

If most browsers' engines implemented tail call optimization, calls such as ```even(1000000)``` should take less than a second to run, but ```even(100000)``` already throws a stack error on Chrome.

For ```sumToN```, it calculates 1 + 2 + 3 + ... + N recursively and returns the result, but throws a stack error at N = 10000 on my browser.

To get around this, write a function `makeStackSafe` that takes in a tail-recursive function as an argument, and returns a stack safe version of it, meaning that calling it with high values might take a long time to compute, but will not result in an error. It has to support mutual tail-recursion as well.

As a hint, you may want to look up on trampolines.

The test cases will be the same as the example test cases, but with the inputs changed to prevent hardcoding: 

Your code should be optimised enough to not cause a timeout for inputs of n between 100 000 000 and 200 000 000.
```javascript
let evenStackSafe = makeStackSafe(n => n === 0 ? true : oddStackSafe(n-1));
let oddStackSafe = makeStackSafe(n => n === 0 ? false : evenStackSafe(n-1));
evenStackSafe(100000000) === true;; //Should not throw an error
let sumToNStackSafe = (n, acc = 0) => n === 0 ? acc : sumToNStackSafe(n-1, acc+n);
sumToNStackSafe(100000000); //Should not throw an error
```
